📅 The 90-Day Emergency Triage Plan
You will split your daily time 50/50: 2 hours on Projects/ML and 2 hours on Placement Prep (DSA/Aptitude).

Weeks 1–4: The Quick-Win Project & DSA Basics
Do not try to build the Advanced GenAI or Fraud system yet. You need a project on your resume now to stop the panic.

The Project (Data Analytics / ML): Build a Predictive Customer Churn or Sales Forecasting project.

Why? It uses clean tabular data, uses libraries like pandas and scikit-learn (which are easy to pick up), and looks highly professional.

Shortcut: Follow a complete end-to-end guided project on YouTube or Kaggle. Do not try to write it from scratch. Copy, understand, tweak the features, and document it.

DSA/Aptitude:

Spend 1 hour a day on Aptitude (Quantitative & Logical Reasoning) using sites like IndiaBIX. Companies use these to filter out 60% of students in the first round.

Spend 1 hour on Basic DSA (Arrays, Strings, and Hashing) on LeetCode or GeeksforGeeks. Master the easy-level problems first.

Weeks 5–8: The "Heavy Hitter" Project & Core DSA
Now that you have one project and basic coding confidence, you build the project that makes you stand out from your peers.

The Project (GenAI / RAG System): Build the LLM-Powered RAG System (Project 3 from our earlier list).

Why? In 2026, companies are desperate for GenAI skills. It relies heavily on APIs (like OpenAI or open-source models) and frameworks like LangChain, meaning it requires less heavy math and more system plumbing. It looks incredibly high-tech on a 3rd-year resume.

DSA/Aptitude: Move to medium-level Array/String problems, and learn basic Searching & Sorting algorithms (Binary Search, Quick Sort). Keep practicing aptitude.

Weeks 9–12: Deployment & Interview Prep
A project on your computer is invisible. A project with a live link gets you hired.

The Project: Take your RAG system or Churn model and host it using Streamlit (a Python library that lets you build a UI in 10 lines of code) and deploy it free on Streamlit Community Cloud or Hugging Face Spaces. Put that live URL right next to the project title on your resume.

Interview Prep: Practice explaining your projects using the STAR format (Situation, Task, Action, Result). Review common SQL queries and Object-Oriented Programming (OOPs) concepts—interviewers love asking 3rd years about these.

